abstract:       Owing to the labor-intensive nature of classic workflows and the lack of real-time predictive capabilities in conventional geotechnical analysis (GA) practices, a paradigm shift toward digitalization and automation is increasingly necessary. However, this transition is significantly hindered by the propagation of uncertainty caused by sparse and heterogeneous geotechnical data. To address these challenges, this study proposes an uncertainty-aware, large language model (LLM)-driven multi-agent system (MAS) for autonomous and near-real-time GAs.
